Day 3: Browser & Page fixture
	Q: What is the difference between Browser & Page fixture
	Ans : 1. Browser fixture will launch Browser only where as Page fixture will launch browser and page
			2. Using Browser we can launch multiple pages on same broser context where as using page we can launch only one page
			3. to do brwoser level settings we need to use Browser fixture only
			4. if we use browser fixture, then we need to create instance of both browser and page inside the test function where as
				if we use page fixture, then no need to create instance of either of them.
	Q: Where to find different version of Playwritht
	Ans : Search for "Playwright version history" in google and select "release note" (playwright.dev/docs/release-notes)

	Q. What is the use of a FIXTURE
	Ans-Fixtures are playwright features which performs certain actions without being called such as 
		Browser fixer will launch the browser without calling it and also closes the browser at the end
		of the execution automatically 

	Q. How to run a test
	Ans - npx playwright test "test file name including the extension"
					e.g - npx playwright test "TestScript.spec.ts"

	Q. How to create browser and page context
	Ans - const browsercontxt = browser.newContext()
    		const pagecontxt = (await browsercontxt).newPage()
	
	Q. Command to view the report
	Ans - npx playwright show-report
		
		
	************ Incomplete ************
	
Day 4: Locators - Understanding CSS Selector to write the Locator
	Types of locators
	1. Playwright specific locators (1st preference) 
	2. CSS Selector (2nd Preference)
	3. Xpath (least preference)
	
	CSS Selector:
	1. id (#<<Id Value>>)
		Syntax:
			a. tagname#idvalue
			b. #idvalue
			c. [id='value']
		NOTE - is the locator is found under <Script> tab then ingnore that locator
	2. class (.<<attribute value>>)
			Syntax:
				a. .ClassValue
				b. .ClassValue.ClassValue (if multiple class values are availabel for the object)
				c. tagname.Classvalue
				d. [class='classvalue']

	3. any attribute ([attribute name='attribute value'])
			Syntax:
			a. TagName[attributeName='AttributeValue']
			b. [attributeName='AttributeValue']
			
	4. Write CSS traversing from Parent to child
			1. Parent locator <Single SPACE> Cild Locator....
			2. page.Locator(.classvalue).first().click
				page.Locator(.classValue).last().click
				page.Locator(.classvalue).nth(4).click (Index starts from 0)
			NOTE - Playwright wont support child to parent approach and also it wont support traversing to siblings
	
	Testing URl - https://rahulshettyacademy.com/seleniumPractise/#/

Day 5 - Understanding xpath and Playwright specific getBy locators
	Locators using XPath
			1. //*[@attributeName='attributeValue'] (//* - this will start searching from top)
				e.g - //*[@id='password']
			2. //tagname[@attributeName='attributeValue'] (//tagname - this will start searching from the first occurance of the mentioned tag)
				e.g - //input[@id='password']
					//input[@id='password'][2] (2 is an index)
					NOTE :
						1. in XPath index starts with 1
						2. in XPath if we are using class value as a locator then we need to provide all the class values given for that particular object

			3. Parent to child
				a. Parent to first child
					//tagname[@attributeName = 'attributevalue']/child object locator
					e.g - //div[@class = 'practive-form']/label
				b. Parent to any child
					//tagname[@attributeName = 'attributevalue']//child object locator
					e.g - //div[@class = 'practive-form']//label
			4. identifying following and preceeding sibling
							//tagname[@attributename = 'attributevalue']//following-sibling::child object locator
							e.g - //label[@for='username']//following-sipling::label

							//tagname[@attributename = 'attributevalue']//preceding-sibling::child object locator
							e.g - //label[@for='username']//preceding-sipling::label
			5.Child to parent
							//tagname[@attributename = 'attributevalue']//parent::parent object locator
							e.g - //label[@for='username']//parent::div
			6. Child to grand parent
							//tagname[@attributename = 'attributevalue']//ancestor::grandparent object locator
							e.g - //label[@for='username']//ancestor::section[2]
			7. Identifying by text value
							//tagname[text()='text value']
							//tagname[text()='text value'][2]
							//tagname[contains(text(),'text value')]
							//*[contains(text(),'text value')]

	PlayWright Build-In locators
		Playwright has 7 build-in locators
			1. getByRole ---> identify the element based on the role
			2. getByText ---> identify the element with its text
			3. getByPlaceholder ---> identify element using 'placeholder' arrtibute. this attribute is available only for text box.
			4. getByTestId ---> identify element using 'data-testid' attribute.
			5. getByAltText ---> Inentify image element using 'Alt' attribute
			6. getByTitle ---> identify element using 'Title' attribute
			7. getByLabel ---> identify element using 'label' tag

			1. getByRole
			2. getByText
				a. getByText('expected string') ---> this will verify instring
				b. getByText('expected string', {exact: true}) ---> this will verify exact match
			3. getByPlaceholder
				getByPlaceholder('place holder value')
			4. getByTestId
				getByyTestId('test id value')
			5. getByAltText
				getByAltText('value of Alt attribute')
			6. getByTitle
				getByTitle('value of Title attribute')
			7. getByLabel
				we use this method in 2 situations
				a. when you have 'for' as an attribute for an element that have been developped using 'label' tag.
					getBylabel('lable text')
				b. when you find <input> tag inside 'label' tag element

				NOTE - In the UI, for any text field when you click on the label next to the specific text/edit field and the 
					curser blinkas in the text/edit field then we can use this method

  

